*[HelpRoot_Install\Upgrading_Acumatica|Updating Acumatica ERP]
*[HelpRoot_Install\Upgrading_on_Azure|Updating Your Acumatica ERP Service on Windows Azure]

To access Acumatica ERP, users must pass authentication to confirm their identity. Then users pass authorization to determine their access rights to system resources, such as suites, modules, and forms. Users can access only the resources they are allowed to use and perform only the actions they are authorized to based on their access rights. In this guide, you will read how to initially configure security for user accounts stored in Acumatica ERP. ==Before You Proceed== You first apply all customizations to your Acumatica ERP instance if the customizations contain newly created forms. You will need to configure access rights to these forms along with standard forms. ==Steps== [[#_3bfd6836-917b-4ca0-8310-60eb8b2a7edf|1. Create User Roles]{br}
[[#_656bf942-2147-4b26-965d-5c4edd41e4ce|2. Set Up Access Rights for User Roles]{br}
[[#_78ae03bb-f26d-4923-a1f4-45b2e7be9400|3. Create User Accounts and Assign User Roles][anchor|#_3bfd6836-917b-4ca0-8310-60eb8b2a7edf] ==1. Create User Roles== You create user roles on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_05|User Roles] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201005|SM201005]) form, shown in the following screenshot, based on the responsibilities of your organization's employees who will work with Acumatica ERP.[anchor|#_19b62e5a-ab84-4907-b43b-4dcafeb09ec8][anchor|#_f708be22-ede4-4e6a-bb5f-6b66cbbdfd79][image:QuickGuides/Images/QG__Configuring_User_Security_Step1.png|popup|400px] For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Role-Based_Access|Role-Based Access].[anchor|#_656bf942-2147-4b26-965d-5c4edd41e4ce] ==2. Set Up Access Rights for User Roles== On the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\SM_65_15_00|Access Rights by Role] ([~/?ScreenId=SM651500|SM651500]) form, shown in the following screenshot, you set up access rights for user roles to Acumatica ERP resources, depending on the tasks performed by users with these user roles.[anchor|#_660a3b93-4765-46f0-9742-627b3b74facb][anchor|#_a9c9a75b-1a6f-463a-b9d8-3bfc8637579f][image:QuickGuides/Images/QG__Configuring_User_Security_Step2.png|popup|400px] For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\US__how_Access_Rights_by_Role_Configuration|To Configure Access Rights for a Selected User Role].[anchor|#_78ae03bb-f26d-4923-a1f4-45b2e7be9400] ==3. Create User Accounts and Assign User Roles== On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_10|Users] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201010|SM201010]) form, which the following screenshot shows, you create accounts for all users of your Acumatica ERP instance and assign roles, which you have created in Step 1, to these users.[anchor|#_80d89634-8751-4d2f-ad03-fe2750e1fea7][anchor|#_ce7e1944-31be-4b34-b9a2-ef1c4fbdd6c6][image:QuickGuides/Images/QG__Configuring_User_Security_Step3.png|popup|450px] For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\US__how_Create_User_Account|To Create a Local User Account]. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Administration\US__con_User_Accounts|User Accounts in Acumatica ERP] *[HelpRoot_Administration\US__con_Access_Rights|User Access Rights] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Role-Based_Access|Role-Based Access] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Roles_and_Access_Rights|Levels of Access Rights]

You configure the sending of push notifications to mobile devices about changes to an entity by using the monitoring business events functionality of Acumatica ERP.{br}

This guide explains how to configure the sending of push notifications to an employee who has been specified as the owner of an opportunity, whether the opportunity is new or its owner has been changed.{br}{TOC}
==Before You Proceed==
Make sure that the ability of the system to send push notifications is turned on for the mobile devices of the users who are supposed to receive the notifications. For details, see ''Management of User Accounts'' in [HelpRoot_Administration\US__con_User_Accounts|User Accounts in Acumatica ERP].
==1. Determine the Generic Inquiry to Be Used for Monitoring==
You use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_80_00|Generic Inquiry] ([~/?ScreenId=SM208000|SM208000]) form to create and modify inquiries. You can create a new generic inquiry based on the {{PX.Objects.CR.CROpportunity}} table or use an existing one that retrieves the following data fields for the {{CROpportunity}} object:[anchor|#_c3ad233b-b904-43c2-9da9-22bfee7a9c28]
*{{OpportunityID}}
*{{OwnerID}}
*{{NoteID}}
*{{Subject}}
*{{Amount}}
*{{Status}}

You fill in the settings in the Summary area of the form ('''Inquiry Title''', '''Site Map Title''', and '''Site Map Location''') at your discretion.{br}

For details on configuring a generic inquiry, see [HelpRoot_ReportingTools\RP__how_tools_GI_DesigningGI|To Design a Generic Inquiry].
==2. Configure a Business Event==
To monitor changes to the user identifier for the opportunity owner, you create a business event on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] ([~/?ScreenId=SM302050|SM302050]) form, as described in [HelpRoot_Administration\AI__how_Business_Event_by_Record_Change|To Monitor Changes of the Business Process Data], using the generic inquiry that you have configured in the first step. The trigger conditions for the business event are a new record (the ''Record Inserted'' operation) or changed {{OwnerID}} field in the {{CROpportunity}} table (the ''Field Changed'' operation); see the screenshot below.[anchor|#_8d42e433-b321-48ab-8df7-151c0537f655][anchor|#_f2a3f8e3-f814-4bf3-933d-9fc71e5b8f3d][image:QuickGuides/Images/QG_Admin_BusinessEvent.png|popup|Business event to monitor changes in opportunity owner|450px]
==3. Configure a Push Notification==
The easiest way to create a push notification that is sent to mobile devices for a business event is to do so while you are creating the event on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] ([~/?ScreenId=SM302050|SM302050]) form: On the table toolbar of the '''Subscribers''' tab, you click '''Create Subscriber''' > '''Mobile Notification'''. This causes the system to open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_04|Mobile Notifications] form with the correct value (the identifier of the generic inquiry you have configured in the first step) selected in the '''Screen''' box.{br}

You fill in the settings of the mobile notification template by using the data fields from the inquiry; see the screenshot below.[anchor|#_2ba00a48-5cd9-45cb-9ced-f9fd83f318f1][anchor|#_02993383-1b84-4b98-8d66-d6dd95ee9c1c][image:QuickGuides/Images/QG__Admin_PushNotification.png|popup|A mobile notification template to notify a user about change of an opportunity owner|450px]
==4. Test the Monitoring of the Change of an Opportunity Owner==
Once the push notification is configured and the business event is activated, each employee that is specified as an owner of an opportunity will receive the push notification about this event. To test the monitoring you have set up, you create a new opportunity and make sure that the assigned user receives the configured push notification; similarly change the owner of an existing opportunity and make sure the user receives the notification.{br}

The system saves information each time it processes the business event, which you can view on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] ([~/?ScreenId=SM502030|SM502030]) form; you can also open this form by clicking the '''View History''' button on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] ([~/?ScreenId=SM302050|SM302050]) form. If something went wrong, you can find all the information you for troubleshooting in the processing history.
